article.headline: Tulsa 78, New Mexico State 66
article.story: TULSA, Okla. (AP) -- Brian Cardwell hit the first two 3-pointers of his career to ignite a 14-1 second-half run, lifting Tulsa to a 78-66 victory over New Mexico State Sunday. Cardwell, a freshman who spent the past four seasons as a pitcher in minor league baseball, had attempted just one 3-pointer in his career coming into the game. But Sunday, Cardwell made both of his 3-point attempts and scored another basket with his toe on the arc to score a career-high 10 points. "Brian is actually a very good shooter," said TU coach John Phillips. "He has good rotation on his shot. And that three was a big basket, we really needed it at that time." Jarius Glenn led Tulsa (3-3) with 16 points and eight rebounds. Jason Parker had 12 points, eight below his average, but five other Golden Hurricane players contributed between 7 and 9 points. Parker's performance comes after Phillips moved him from point guard to shooting guard before Tulsa's previous game. The move seems to be paying dividends. Except for Parker and Glenn's contributions, all of Tulsa's points were scored by first or second-year players, including 9 from Seneca Collins and 8 apiece by Guilherme Teichamann, Kenneth Kelley and Charles Ramsdell. "We've got a lot of guys who can shoot it and we can create mismatches and take advantage of that," Phillips said. "I really liked the way we passed the ball today." John Duane, who came in averaging 29.5 points per game, led New Mexico State (4-2) with 16 points. Detrius Roberson added 14 and James Moore had 10 points and eight rebounds before fouling out. The Aggies rallied from a 13-point deficit to cut Tulsa's lead to 57-52 with 10:12 left. Cardwell starting Tulsa's game-clinching run with his high-arching 3-pointer and Glenn followed that up with a basket. The spurt was capped by Charles Ramsdell's three-point play, giving Tulsa a 71-53 lead with 3:57 to play. Tulsa shot 64 percent in the second half, helping the Golden Hurricane build on its 36-31 halftime lead. Tulsa outrebounded NMSU 34-31 and forced the Aggies into 42.9 percent shooting and 17 turnovers.
